\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Visual Prolog's BGI system provides over 70 graphics predicates, ranging from higher-level calls (like {\uldb\cf11 setviewport}{\i\v setviewport_5}{\b\i , }{\uldb\cf11 bar3d}{\i\v bar3d_6}, and {\uldb\cf11 drawpoly}{
\i\v drawpoly_1}) to bit-oriented predicates (like {\uldb\cf11 getpixel}{\v getpixel_3} and {\uldb\cf11 putpixel}{\i\v putpixel_3}
). The BGI graphics system allows you to draw lines, arcs, circles, polygons, and other shapes; it supports numerous fill and line styles; and it provides several text fonts that you can magnify, justify, and orient horizontally or vertically.
\par Visual Prolog supplies only bindings to the Borland Graphics Interface (See the Visual Prolog ..\\BGIBIND subdirectories).
\par \pard\plain \s54\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b\ul This means :}
\par \pard\plain \s32\fi-284\li284\sa60\tx284\tx567 \f5\fs20 {\f1 \'b7\tab }that Visual Prolog {\ul supplies}
 BGI.CON and BGI.PRE files that contain declarations of constants, domains, and predicates you must include in your program for using of BGI system. Add path to these files {\b ;..\\BGIBIND\\INCLUDE} into your {\b Options|Project|Directories|Libraries}
 list edit entry. Also Visual Prolog supplies BGIBIND.LIB libraries that contain  {\i gluecode }for calling of some BGI functions. You must specify that the library BGIBIND.LIB should be linked in. Add {\b ;..\\BGIBIND\\LIB\\DOS\\BGIBIND.LIB}
 for realmode DOS programs and {\b ;..\\BGIBIND\\LIB\\DOS\\BGIBIND.LIB }for protected mode DOS programs into {\b Options|Project|Directories|Libraries} list edit entry.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }and that Visual Prolog {\ul does not contain}
 the Borland Graphics Interface libraries (*.LIB files), graphics device drivers (*.BGI files), stroked character fonts (*.CHR files) and other files of BGI system. So if your Prolog programs must use BGI than you must install on your computer Borland C++
. Then you must specify that the C++ BGI library BGI.LIB should be linked in. Add into {\b Options|Project|Directories|Libraries} list edit entry path and name of the BGI library. 
\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 More detailed information on how to use BGI bindings you will find in Visual Prolog  \\BGIBIND\\README.TXT file. See also {\uldb\cf11 Building and Running a Stand-Alone BGI Executable}{\v 
Building_and_Running_a_Stand_Alone_BGI_Executable}
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 BGI.CON contains constants declarations to improve the readability of your programs. This allows you to use symbolic names that correspond to the action of the argument rather than entering an integer value. For e
xample, BGI.CON defines {\b\i PI} = 3.14159265359 and {\b\i red} = 4; most of the other values used in the BGI are also defined in BGI.CON in terms of their symbolic names.
\par You should load BGI.CON and BGI.PRE into the {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt Visual Prolog}} editor and take a look at them before trying to do anything substantial with the BGI predicates.
