\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Every PC has some kind of video adapter. This can be a Monochrome Display Adapter (MDA) for a basic text-only display, or it can be one capable of 
displaying graphics, such as a Color Graphics Adapter (CGA), an Enhanced Graphics Adapter (EGA), or a Hercules Monochrome Graphics Adapter. Each adapter can operate in a variety of modes; the mode specifies whether the screen displays 80 or 40 columns (te
xt mode only), the display resolution (graphics mode only), and the display type (color, monochrome, or black & white).
\par \pard\plain \s32\fi-284\li284\sa60\tx284\tx567 \f5\fs20 {\f1 \'b7\tab }In {\b\i text mode}{\b ,} your PC's screen is divided into cells, usually 80 columns wide by 25 lines high. Each cell consists of an attribute and 
a character. The character is the displayed ASCII character, while the attribute specifies how the character is displayed (its color, intensity, etc.). In text mode you can use {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt Visual Prolog}}
's screen- and window-handling predicates).
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }In {\b\i graphics mode}{\b ,} your PC's screen {\deleted\revauth17\revdttm-2047518179 is divided into}{\revised\revauth17\revdttm-2047518179 consists of} pixels, which is short for {\i picture elements}
; each pixel displays a single dot on the screen. The number of pixels (the resolution) depends on the type of video adapter connected to your system and the mode that adapter is in. In graphics mode, you use {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt 
Visual Prolog}}'s BGI predicates to create graphic displays on the screen: You can draw lines and shapes, fill enclosed areas with patterns, and control the color of each pixel.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 In text mode, on-screen locations are given in rows and columns, where rows increase from top to bottom, and columns increase from left to right. {\revised\revauth17\revdttm-2047518179 
\par }In graphics mode, on-screen locations are given as ({\i x,y}) coordinates, with the upper-left corner in position (0,0); the x coordinates increase from left to right, and the y coordinates increase from top to bottom.
