\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 The graphics screen consists of an array of pixels; each pixel produ
ces a single (colored) dot on the screen. The pixel's value does not specify the precise color directly; it is an index into a color table called a palette. The palette entry corresponding to a given pixel value contains the exact color information for th
at pixel.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 
This indirection scheme has a number of implications. Though the hardware might be capable of displaying many colors, only a subset of those colors can be displayed at any given time. The number of colors that can be displayed at any one time is e
qual to the number of entries in the palette (the palette's size). For example, on an EGA, the hardware can display 64 different colors, but only 16 of them at a time; the EGA palette's size = 16.
\par The size of the palette determines the range of values a pixel can assume, from 0 to (size - 1). The {\uldb\cf11 getmaxcolor}{\v getmaxcolor_1} predicate returns the highest valid pixel value (size - 1) for the current graphics driver and mode.
\par In this chapter, we often use the term color, such as the current drawing color, fill co
lor, and pixel color. In fact, this color is like a pixel value: it's an index into the palette. Only the palette determines the true color on the screen. By manipulating the palette, you can change the actual color displayed on the screen even though the
 pixel values (drawing color, fill color, etc.) have not changed.
\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b Background and Drawing Color
\par }The {\i background color} always corresponds to pixel value 0. When an area is cleared to the {\i background color}, that area's pixels are simply set to 0.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 The {\i drawing color} is the value to which pixels are set when lines or shapes are drawn. You select a {\i drawing color} with {\i setcolor(N)}, where N is a valid pixel value for the current palette.
