\par You can determine the on-screen size (in pixels) of a given text string by calling two predicates; one measures the string's height and the other measures its width.
\par The available fonts include a standard built-in bit-mapped font and several stroked fonts. You can enlarge them all, as well as "stretch" or "compress" the stroked fonts to your own liking. You can specify whether a string of text prints horizontally or v
ertically, and you can control text justification.
\par For an explanation of text direction, see {\uldb\cf11 settextstyle}{\i\v settextstyle_3}; for a discussion of text justification, see {\uldb\cf11 settextjustify}{\i\v settextjustify_2}. Text sizes (standard and user-defined) are described under {
