\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Depending on your graphics adapter, your system has between one and eight  screen-page buffers, which are areas in memory where individual whole-screen images are stored dot-by-dot. You can specify which scre
en page is the active one (where graphics predicates place their output) and which is the visual page (the one displayed on screen) with setactivepage and setvisualpage, respectively.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 Once your screen's in a graphics mode, you can define a {\uldb\cf11 viewport}{\v Some_Words_about_Viewports} (a rectangular "virtual screen") on your screen with a call to {\uldb\cf11 setviewport}{\v setviewport_5}
. You define the viewport's position in terms of absolute screen coordinates, and specify whether clipping is On (active) or Off. You clear the viewport with {\uldb\cf11 clearviewport}{\i\v clearviewport_0}
. To find out the current viewport's absolute screen coordinates and clipping status, call {\uldb\cf11 getviewsettings}{\i\v getviewsettings_5}. 
\par You can clear the whole screen in one fell swoop with a call to {\uldb\cf11 cleardevice}{\i\v cleardevice_0}
; this predicate erases the entire screen and homes the current position (CP) in the viewport, but leaves all other graphics system settings intact (the line, fill, and text styles, the palette, the viewport settings, etc.).
\par \pard\plain \s28\sa80\keepn\tx2835 \b\f5\cf2 \page {\cs22\super #{\footnote \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20 {\cs22\super #} Some_Words_about_Viewports}} {\cs22\super ${\footnote \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20 {\cs22\super $} Some Words about Viewports}} {
