 CBB ("Overview_btn","JumpId(`VIP.HLP',`The_Borland_Graphics_Interface')")}} Some Words about Viewports
\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt Visual Prolog}}{\i  }
provides predicates for creating and managing viewports on your screen in graphics mode. If you are not familiar with BGI viewports, you should read this brief overview.
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 
In BGI graphics mode, you can define a rectangular area on your PC's video screen; this is a viewport. When your BGI graphics program outputs drawings, etc., the viewport acts as the virtual screen. The rest of the screen (outside the viewport) remains un
touched. You define a viewport in terms of screen coordinates with a call to the {\uldb\cf11 setviewport}{\v setviewport_5} predicate.
\par BGI viewports are similar to windows, but they are unbuffered and are defined in terms of your PC's graphics resolution--not its text resolution. 
\par The default viewport is the entire screen, which is the same as calling:
\par \pard\plain \s19\li284\keep \f11\fs20 {\f5 setviewport(0,0,639,199)]}   in high-resolution mode on a CGA
\par {\f5 setviewport(0,0,319,199)]}   in low-resolution mode on a CGA
\par {\f5 setviewport(0,0,639,349)]}   in high-resolution mode on an EGA
