\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Running your graphics programs from within {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt PDC Prolog}}
's development environment is the easiest way to learn about the BGI in general. Programs will run exactly the same way when you compile them to .EXE files. Here's what you need to do:
\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 Include BGI.PRE and BGI.CON (use the {\i include}{\b  }keyword in your program).
\par Place the .BGI and .CHR files on the current directory, or give their path to {\uldb\cf11 initgraph}{\i\v initgraph_5}.
\par Case in Point: A good way to organize your BGI files is to have only one copy of the .CHR and .BGI files, placed (for example) in the directory C:\\PROLOG\\BGI. You can give this path in your call to initgraph like this:
\par \pard\plain \s38\sb120\keep \f11\fs20 initgraph(0, 0, _, _, "c\\\\prolog\\\\bgi"),
\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 It's also good idea to use the standard predicate {\b envsymbol}. You could then use the DOS SET command to tell {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt PDC Prolog}} where the BGI drivers are placed, like so:

\par \pard\plain \s19\li284\keep \f11\fs20 SET bgipath = c:\\prolog\\bgi
\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Then your {\field\fldedit{\*\fldinst  title }{\fldrslt PDC Prolog}} program will be able to read where the drivers are located if you make these calls:
\par \pard\plain \s38\sb120\keep \f11\fs20 envsymbol("bgipath",BGIpath), \line /* Binds BGIpath to value of bgipath */
\par initgraph(0,0,_,_,BGIpath), \line /* Tells initgraph the path name set with SET */
