\par \pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 This is the most advanced method of generating an executable file from your BGI graphics program. It's also t
he most specialized; you need to know which graphics adapter is attached to the run-time computer, because you'll be linking the graphics driver software directly into your finished product at compile-and-link time. The advantage to this method is that yo
ur finished product will be a true stand-alone application. There's no need to make the .BGI and .CHR files available at run time, since they're already built into your program. One disadvantage is that the size of your executable is larger than it would 
be with the other methods already described.
