\par \pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b Flow patterns}\tab (i, i, i, i, o){\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 Saves a bit image of the specified rectangular region to memory
\par {\b Remarks
\par }\pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b getimage} saves a bit image of a rectangular region on the screen to memory. {\i Left, Top, Right}, and {\i Bottom} define the on-screen rectangle. You can use the variable {\i BitMap} to refer to the image.
\par There is one constraint on {\i BitMap}-variables: They can be manipulated like other variables (used as arguments to predicates, unified with other variables, etc.), but they can't be asserted into or retracted from a database.
\par This is because database strings being asserted and retracted must be null-terminated (ended with a NULL byte: 0000 0000) 
and there is no guarantee that there won't be a NULL byte in the middle of an image string. However, using the new binary block predicates operating on files and the external database system, they can be stored and retrieved here.{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b Fail
\par }\pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 Never fails.{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b Errors
\par }\pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 No errors.{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s26\sb120\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b Example
\par }\pard\plain \s38\sb120\keep \f11\fs20 include "BGI.PRE"
