\par {\b Remarks
\par }\pard\plain \s16\sa120 \f5\fs20 {\b initgraph} initializes the graphics system by loading a graphics driver from disk (or validating a registered driver), and puts the system into graphics mode. {\b initgraph} binds {\i NewDriver} and {\i NewMode}
 to the actual graphics driver and mode.
\par You can tell {\b initgraph} to use a particular graphics driver and mode, or to auto-detect the attached video adapter at run time and pick the corresponding driver. If you tell {\b initgraph} to auto-detect, it calls {\b\uldb\cf11 detectgraph}{\b\v 
detectgraph_2} to select a graphics driver and mode. {\b initgraph} also resets all graphics settings to their defaults (current position, palette, color, viewport, etc.).
\par Normally, {\b initgraph} loads a graphics driver by first allocating memory (from Prolog's heap manager) for the driver, then loading the appropr
iate .BGI file from disk. As an alternative to this dynamic loading scheme, you can link a graphics driver (or several of them) directly into your executable program file.
\par {\i PathtoDriver} specifies the directory path in which {\b initgraph} will look for the graphics drivers (the .BGI files). {\b initgraph} first looks in the path specified in {\i PathtoDriver}
, then (if the files aren't there) in the current directory. Accordingly, if {\i PathtoDriver} is empty (""), the driver files (*.BGI) must be in the current directory.
\par {\i Graphdriver} is an integer that specifies the graphics driver to be used. You can use the following symbolic constants, defined in BGI.PRE, instead of the integers.
